    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2130343">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2130343">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2130343)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2130343">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1718084"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1413155350 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 Oct 2014 23:09</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2130343">
									

<p>You know, a few years ago, the first time I read SCP-231, I flipped through the discussion section, and found a bunch of people talking to clef about ways to make the article seem more horrific. I think I actually saw the guy who told him to imply that it was a child. But then I thought to myself, what if that <em>is</em> procedure 110-Montauk? The article never told us what the procedure actually entailed, but it spent plenty of time telling us how nebulously awful it was.</p>
<p>Assuming that this were an actual article for an actual, pan-continental, shadowy containment foundation, wouldn't they try to leave all that horrible stuff out, so as to keep morale up?</p>
<p>Unless of course, the horror is what it <em>took</em>.</p>
<p>And now we have this tale, which basically summed up my little fan theory. Of course I'm going to upvote it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
