					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bellbloom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2828072); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2828072&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250852" alt="Bellbloom" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2828072)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/bellbloom" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2828072); return false;" >Bellbloom</a></span> <span class="odate time_1472854752 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Sep 2016 22:19</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2584473">
									

<p>The other thing about this is that we're to assume from 231 that Scarlet King, being the harbringer of destruction that it is, isn't just rewarding 110-Montauk with compliance out of the goodness of its heart. The point is that it's <em>kept at bay</em> by the fear and association with horrible acts - they're like the wall keeping it from being born; either revulsion of the Scarlet King exists, or the Scarlet King does. I guess the phrasing in the Tale is different, but like&#8230;even if it knew that everything that was happening was fake, would it really be able to do anything about it, when there's thousands and thousands of agents going around living with the debilitating fear that they have participated in 110-Montauk multiple times?</p>
<p>As far as the Tales about agents who refuse to take amnestics, just because the Foundation is unwilling to rape a child doesn't mean they're not willing to do shitty things. They're a morally grey organization after all. They probably have to plant false memories or delusions in agents' heads every once in a while in order to continue keeping the creature at bay.</p>
<p>Anyway, enough meta, I absolutely love this Tale and theory, it completely redeems 231 and the entire wiki for me.</p>

